        <h2>UNDER PRESSURE: WHEN THINGS GO WRONG</h2>

        <p>
            Real debate isn't polished. You'll blank. You'll forget evidence. You'll stumble mid-sentence. Here's how to recover without losing the round.
        </p>

        <h3>You Blank Mid-Speech</h3>

        <div class="quick-tactic">
            <div class="tactic-header">Recovery Protocol</div>
            <div class="tactic-title">The 3-Second Reset</div>
            <p>Your brain freezes. The clock's running. Here's your recovery:</p>
            <ol>
                <li><strong>Don't panic-talk:</strong> "Um, uh, so basically..." makes it worse. Take a breath instead.</li>
                <li><strong>Use a bridge phrase:</strong> "Let me emphasize the key point here—" buys you 2 seconds to find your thread.</li>
                <li><strong>Return to your strongest argument:</strong> "What matters most is [your best point]." Judges won't penalize repetition of strong content.</li>
                <li><strong>If you can't recover:</strong> "I'll return to that point if time permits. Moving on—" No one expects perfection.</li>
            </ol>
            <p><strong>What judges actually think:</strong> Brief pauses read as thoughtful. Panicked rambling reads as unprepared. Silence beats garbage.</p>
        </div>

        <h3>You Forget Your Evidence</h3>

        <div class="quick-tactic">
            <div class="tactic-header">Recovery Protocol</div>
            <div class="tactic-title">Evidence Under Pressure</div>
            <p>You cited a study earlier. Now you can't remember the numbers. Options:</p>
            <ol>
                <li><strong>Generalize confidently:</strong> "The research consistently shows [general finding]" is better than fumbling for exact stats.</li>
                <li><strong>Use the hedge-and-pivot:</strong> "The exact figure is in my notes—but the trend is clear: [pattern]."</li>
                <li><strong>Callback without specifics:</strong> "As the MIT study I cited demonstrated..." Judges often remember you cited it even if they don't recall numbers.</li>
                <li><strong>Worst case:</strong> "Multiple studies confirm this." Vague but not a lie. Move forward.</li>
            </ol>
            <p><strong>Never:</strong> Make up numbers. Judges may have written down what you actually said. Getting caught fabricating destroys credibility.</p>
        </div>

        <h3>You Mispronounce or Misspeak</h3>

        <div class="quick-tactic">
            <div class="tactic-header">Recovery Protocol</div>
            <div class="tactic-title">The Quick Correct</div>
            <p>You said the wrong name, mangled a word, or misstated your own position.</p>
            <ol>
                <li><strong>Correct immediately and move on:</strong> "—Piketty, rather. His research shows..." Don't dwell on it.</li>
                <li><strong>If you're not sure you erred:</strong> Keep going. Most missteps go unnoticed. Correcting a non-error wastes time.</li>
                <li><strong>If caught in CX:</strong> "I misspoke. What I meant was [correct version]." Honesty > defensiveness.</li>
            </ol>
            <p><strong>Key insight:</strong> Judges have seen hundreds of debates. Minor stumbles don't matter. Recovery grace does.</p>
        </div>

        <h3>You're Losing the Judges</h3>

        <div class="quick-tactic">
            <div class="tactic-header">Recovery Protocol</div>
            <div class="tactic-title">The Mid-Round Pivot</div>
            <p>You can feel it: confused faces, skeptical body language, judges not flowing. You're losing them.</p>
            <ol>
                <li><strong>Simplify immediately:</strong> "Let me put this simply: [one clear sentence]."</li>
                <li><strong>Acknowledge complexity:</strong> "I know this is dense. Here's what you need to remember: [core point]."</li>
                <li><strong>Tell a brief story:</strong> Humans respond to narrative. "Consider what this means in practice: [30-second concrete example]."</li>
                <li><strong>Repeat your voting issue:</strong> "At the end of this round, ask yourself one question: [your framing]. That's what I'm proving."</li>
            </ol>
            <p><strong>Warning sign:</strong> If judges stop writing, you've lost them. Change something—pace, content, energy.</p>
        </div>

        <h3>CX Under Cognitive Load</h3>

        <div class="quick-tactic">
            <div class="tactic-header">Recovery Protocol</div>
            <div class="tactic-title">Real-Time CX Survival</div>
            <p>Cross-examination is the only phase where you can't call prep time. Your brain is splitting: listen, think, respond, plan. Here's how to survive:</p>
            <ol>
                <li><strong>When you don't understand:</strong> "Can you rephrase that?" is always legitimate. It also buys 5 seconds.</li>
                <li><strong>When you don't know:</strong> "I'd need to see the specific evidence to address that" is better than guessing.</li>
                <li><strong>When trapped:</strong> "I see where you're going. Let me clarify my actual position—" Don't answer the question as asked if it's a trap.</li>
                <li><strong>When being rapid-fired:</strong> "Let me answer your first question fully before we move on." Slows their pace.</li>
            </ol>
            <p><strong>The secret:</strong> You don't have to answer every question the way they want. You have to look reasonable while protecting your case. Judges reward composure, not compliance.</p>
        </div>

        <h3>Your Opponent Made a Point You Can't Answer</h3>

        <div class="quick-tactic">
            <div class="tactic-header">Recovery Protocol</div>
            <div class="tactic-title">The Strategic Concession</div>
            <p>They made a genuinely good point. You don't have a response. Now what?</p>
            <ol>
                <li><strong>Concede narrowly:</strong> "That's fair on [specific sub-point]. But notice it doesn't touch [your main argument]."</li>
                <li><strong>Reframe stakes:</strong> "Even granting their point, the question remains: [bigger issue they haven't addressed]."</li>
                <li><strong>Minimize impact:</strong> "Interesting point. But does it change the outcome? My core case still stands because [reason]."</li>
                <li><strong>What NOT to do:</strong> Pretend it didn't happen. Judges noticed. Ignoring strong arguments looks evasive.</li>
            </ol>
            <p><strong>Remember:</strong> You don't need to win every argument. You need to win the debate. Strategic concession can actually build credibility.</p>
        </div>

        <h3>You're Running Out of Time</h3>

        <div class="quick-tactic">
            <div class="tactic-header">Recovery Protocol</div>
            <div class="tactic-title">The 30-Second Crunch</div>
            <p>You have 30 seconds left and two more arguments to cover. Triage:</p>
            <ol>
                <li><strong>Drop your weakest remaining point.</strong> Don't mention it. Judges won't miss what they never heard.</li>
                <li><strong>Hit your voting issue:</strong> "Here's what this comes down to: [single sentence]."</li>
                <li><strong>Trust your best argument:</strong> If you made one strong point well, trust it. Don't dilute with rushed additions.</li>
                <li><strong>End with confidence:</strong> A strong final sentence beats two mumbled points. "For these reasons, I urge a [affirmative/negative] decision."</li>
            </ol>
            <p><strong>Never:</strong> Speed up so much judges can't follow. A clear 80% beats a garbled 100%.</p>
        </div>

