        <h2>THE UNIVERSAL RESPONSE FRAMEWORK</h2>

        <p>
            When none of the above fits, or you need a general structure, use this:
        </p>

        <div class="quick-tactic">
            <div class="tactic-header">Quick Tactic</div>
            <div class="tactic-title">The A-R-E Framework</div>
            <p>For any argument you face, respond with:</p>
            <ol>
                <li><strong>Acknowledge:</strong> "I understand the point you're making about [X]."</li>
                <li><strong>Respond:</strong> "Here's why that doesn't hold: [your response]."</li>
                <li><strong>Extend:</strong> "And this actually supports my position because [connection to your case]."</li>
            </ol>
            <p>This three-step move is ancient. Cicero used it in his orations against Catiline—acknowledge the force of opposition, show why it fails, return to your case. It works because it respects your audience's intelligence while holding your ground. Aristotle would have recognized it as building <em>ethos</em> through fairness.</p>
            <p>Takes 15-30 seconds per argument. Works on anything. Practice it until it's automatic.</p>
            <p><strong>Example:</strong> "I understand the concern about cost. But the research shows these programs pay for themselves within five years. And that long-term savings is exactly why my framework of sustainable policy should guide this debate."</p>
        </div>

